description.text:
This is a dice tower for all dice playing board games. The gate can be lifted up so the dices do not roll on the table.  No support structure needed when printing, however, requires a calibrated printer. 
Update 25-09-2017: New version uploaded. High and low resolution with added window borders, plant and better front gate. Small hole also added on the bottom for a small light for the dungeon. 
Created in Solidworks

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

20%
Update: Version 3 is up.

Printed on UM2 with 0.15mm layer PLA and ABS. Remove support when done. Took about 22 hours to make.   
Small sized dice tower is about 10 cm in height without buildtin support. (Recommended for small printer)
Castle_w_top_w_support_V2.STL is a full size dice tower with a larger platform at top and with builtin support. (Recommended for larger printer)  
Castle_no_top_w_support.STL is full size without the top and with support for the arc.   
Castle_w_top_no_support.STL is a full size dice tower without the support structure in the arc.

description.text:
A simple attachment for an industry standard 2x15mmx60mm camera rig
to hold a common 30mm training weight as a counter balance. blog post:
http://marcuswolschon.blogspot.com/2011/04/counter-weight-for-shoulder-rig.html photo album:
https://picasaweb.google.com/Marcus.Wolschon/20110325Bis201105ShulterRigBauen?feat=directlink forum post:
http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?88,75536 project in my personal wiki:
https://sourceforge.net/userapps/mediawiki/marcuswolschon/index.php?title=Projects/Camera/ShoulderRig#status IF YOU HAVE NO ACCESS TO A 3D-PRINTER AND CAN't FINE SOMEONE ELSE TO PRINT THESE FOR YOU, YOU CAN HAVE SHAPEWAYS PRINT THESE FOR YOU:
http://www.shapeways.com/shops/marcuswolschon?section=Camera+and+Filming

Print both parts and one MiddlePiece of the original shoulder-rig thing.
I suggest to assembly Counterweight and Counterweight_Part2 with first, then take them apart, assemble them again with the actual weight and then attach that assembly to MiddlePiece.
This way it's easier to have the M5 or 1/4" bolts cut their way. Both pieces are designed such that they clamp the weight securely between 2 ramps.
So the weight cannot shift no matter how much the diameter of it's actual center hole deviates from it's specified 30mm.
All weight rests on the 15mm rods.
Nonetheless you should print these with 0.5 - 0.6 infill to give it enough strength. You need either 2 M5 wing-bolts for the outer holes or one 1/5" winged bolt for the center holes.

I need teaspoons to dispense nutrients to my hydroponic gardening system but I don't like to use the one I use for cooking. Instead of going out and buying some I decided to print my own. I had seen that TMR had designed some earlier but I didn't need quite as long a handle and I also wanted to label them with their quantity. It's a really cool feeling to not be bound by the limits of store-bought measuring spoons so... just because I could I printed a 13/16 teaspoon. yay!
One thing I would have liked to do is to also label them with their metric equivalent (ie. 1 tsp = 5 ml and 1 tbs = 15 ml) as that stuff can be really helpful when your trying to convert between the two.

Some printing tips:
-- don't use a raft - this gives you a much better chance of it being water tight
-- get the nozzle as low as you can to the surface at startup and really have the plastic get smushed in so that it doesn't curl and warp as much (happened to me on my first print).
-- adjust some of the fill properties (solid surface thickness --> 3 and extra shells --> 2 or 3) That should do it!

title: CTC / Flashforge Front Panel Power Switch

description.text:
Quick and easy way to move the power switch to the front where its more convenient.  
On these clones they switch the AC power to the supply rather then the DC output like on other printers.  So i designed a way to add a front panel power switch thats recessed so it can't be accidentally bumped while printing.  
Installation is easy, you need a 1 1/2" hole saw, drill the hole where you want it, the lower left corner is a good place as nothing is in the way there behind the front panel and there is plenty of space between the power supply and the front panel, then you use the mount as a template to mark and drill the other four holes to mount it.  I used 3mm cap screws because i had them on hand, but any machine screw would work, or you could simply use something like a sheet metal screw and screw into the wood panel.  
The switch is just your standard push in panel switch, 12.5mm wide by 20mm tall.  To wire this up make sure the printer is unplugged from the outlet or unplug the cord from the back, then remove the red jumper wire at the power inlet, they used a short jumper to go from the power inlet to the switch, and install the wires to your new switch to the two points that the jumper was installed.  This puts your new switch in series with the original.  
For normal use you turn on the back switch and leave it on, then turn the printer on and off from the added front panel switch.  Easy... no wire cutting or splicing!
75% infill, standard settings.

Face it, filing plastic models is a fact of life when you work with a 3D printer. This is tedious work, which can leave your hand but a withered claw! This object is an ergonomic handle for small "hobby" or needle files which are commonly used to finish 3D-printed models. The cross section is a Relaux triangle, which is slightly sculpted in order to provide a pencil-style grip which enables fine control and reduces fatigue. . These handles are designed to fit needle files with a cylindrical shank 3mm in diamter. Examples include http://www.homedepot.com/p/Nicholson-5-1-2-in-Assorted-Hobby-Craft-Mini-File-Set-6-Piece-42030L/203336567 and http://www.amazon.com/Nicholson-Piece-Hobby-Carded-Length/dp/B00002N5JT. Additionally, the handles may be scaled in order to fit other sizes and types of files. In addition to the file handles, a matching stand is also provided. It holds the files securely and arranges them for easy access. A center cavity in the stand can be used to store another tool which you are always reaching for, such as a pair of tweezers. I hope someone will find these useful, print them out, and upload a few photos. I'm not a very good hand model, I'm afraid.

Both the file handles and the stands should be printed in the given orientations. The file handle model features a thin disk which promotes better adhesion to the build surface; it should be easy to remove with a knife, machete, or oxygen torch. No supports should be used to print either the file handle or base.  
The handles are assembled onto the files by a press fit. I have hand the best results by clamping the cutting surface of the file vertically between two pieces of wood in a bench vise, and hammering the handle down onto the file. If you have a propane torch, assembly can be greatly eased by heating the file shank (but be careful not to anneal the cutting edges!)

title: Co-Processed Servo Motor Test

description.text: I co-processed a servo motor into my print job so that the printer would lay filament down over it. I then used an Arduino to drive the servo motor, so it could break the build adhesion forces and move itself off the build plate. This is a test piece for a larger project I am designing. Please check out my blog here if you want to know more or are unfamiliar with co-processing: https://printeraction.wordpress.com/

Materials:
This servo motor: https://www.sparkfun.com/products/9347
An Arduino Place a small piece of blue tape on the top of the servo so that the filament can stick to it easily. When the printer starts to print the flat overhang, pause the print and place the servo motor in its place, with the smaller 180 degree servo horn attached and rotated such that its touching the ground when the servo is laid down horizontally (as it would be in the part). Continue the print, and watch the printer lay filament down on the surface of the servo motor. Once the print is done, plug the Arduino in and run Arduino's "Sweep" example code, but change the delay to 700 ms. This will get the motor to pry itself off of the build plate! If you want to learn more about coprocessing, please check out my blog here: https://printeraction.wordpress.com/

description.text: This top shoulder reinforcement plate fits exactly onto the front section of a Lumenier QAV250 frame. We'll make adjustments and create a V2 based upon your experience and feedback. UPDATE 4/19: Just tested it with only the top plate and it wasn't strong enough. You need to print out 2 copies to use on the top and bottom for double support. A coin cell battery holder parameterized for the number and size of cells and wall thicknesses. Print to hold the cells at the bottom of their slots by friction, and push them up via the bottom slot and then grab the sides from the top. This design is chunkier than some but it is going to live and work in a toolbox so the robustness is a feature. If you want to build a multi-cell battery look here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:267438 . 30 volts in the size of a D-Cell! One end is marked with a hole to keep track of relative state of charge or whatever.

The slots are supposed to be a light friction fit for the cells. Imperfections from X and Y inaccuracies of a print job may narrow the slot enough to enhance the grep. Call it a feature you can adjust with the slot width. On a Davinci I had to use a raft and support to keep the initial islands from getting knocked off the build platform as the overhangs of the bottom slot curled up. Your slicer/printer may be able to get away with just using support instead.

description.text: As part of Boise Code Camp (http://boisecodecamp.com/), the company I work for sponsored a Sumo Bot competition. Everyone used the same hardware, the deciding factor was the code. The company bought Sparkfun Redbots (https://www.sparkfun.com/products/12697) and I designed and printed the sumo shields. The Redbot was configured with 2 reflectance in the front and one in the back, and an ultrasonic sensor was added. The main purpose of the front and back shields was to protect the reflectance sensors and work as a mount for the ultrasonic sensor. Front and back shields are angled at 10 deg. Both shields print without support and clip onto Redbot for easy installation and removal.

The shields were printed using:
PLA
Shells: 3
Fill: 40%
Speed: 80/100 (mm/s) Time:
Front Shield: ~ 3.5 - 4 hrs
Back Shield: ~ 1.5 hrs

comments.text: One thing we noticed during the competition is that there's a tendency for the front shields to come partially off when the bots run into each other.  If the front edge of the shield is too low, it'll lift the wheels from the surface, reducing the bots' ability to move.  I'd suggest extending the top center support further into the bot (over the first round hole) then drilling a hole through it so you've got a way to lock the top of the shield onto the bot.

title: Model Rocket Nosecone and Tailfin Section for 30mm (or 1.25") Cardboard Tubes. 29mm motor.

description.text: I designed these pieces to turn a 30mm cardboard tube I had laying around into a true model rocket that accepts 29mm motors. This works perfectly with the cardboard tubes from a Reynolds Wrap aluminum foil roll. I first fiberglassed the cardboard tube with 1 layer of fiberglass and epoxy, to make it stronger. Fiberglassing wasn't a necessary step, but will produce a stronger rocket. This also made the tube slightly wider but that difference is so small it should not matter. I slightly undersized the OD of the parts so it will work with either fiberglassed or non-fiberglassed tubes. My tube measured approx 28.6mm inner diameter. I highly recommend using a raft for both prints. Both objects should be printed upright with a raft. This means the nosecone should be printed pointing up with a raft under its bottom. The tailfin should also be printed upright with a raft to minimize lifting. Even with the raft I still unfortunately experienced some lift, but it was not enough to mess up the print. Once finsihed, just remove the rafts, and slide into the tube. It should be a tight fit, with a small amount of resistance. The tailfin should be epoxied in place. The nosecone should be attached using a shock cord.

If anyone would like a version of this dock to fit the LG G3 without the case, please let me know and I will upload it! Thank you! description.text:
This is my suggestion on a Hall sensor mount on the P3Steel.
Include:
1) Hall sensor wire
2) Hall sensor mount
3) Magnet mount on the y-axis Print and enjoy

I have seen someone (but can not find my reference again) who used a 3 pin DuPont female pin header plug to mount the hall sensor in. Then I have searched for a sensor switching hall sensor that required a minimum of electronics. This resulted in this proposal for how to mount the X and Y endstops on the P3steel.
You will need:
  • 2X3 appropriated length Wire
  • 4 DuPont 3 plugs with femal pins
  • 2 10k ohm (or there about)
  • 2 Hall switch sensors (A1104EUA-T - or the like)
  • 3mm ø and 10mm long magnets (preferable strong ones)
  • at bit of M3 screws and nuts
    • So lets dig in. 1) Make the wire by crimping the outer two female pins with the 10k ohm pull up resistor (see image with the plug on the table) and in the other end crimp a normal 3 pin plug. Mount the pins in the plug resulting in a wire with a 3 pin plug in both ends and in one end with the pull up resistor.
    2) Print the parts and when printing of the X-Endstop holder is done then (while the plastic is still hot) insert the DuPont plug and let cool. The rest of the parts can be cooled and taken off as normal.
    3) Remove your hotbed and mount the Y-axis magnet holder. If you have the newest version there should be holes in the laser cut parts (use the small screw one) then just screw ion the holder. If not (use the more bulky one) the mount and zip-tie the mount on the Y-frame. Remount your hotbed.
    4) Y-endstop: Rap a bit of isolation tape around the plug and mount in the holes on the back plate (I mounted it closest to the electronics - but feel free to mount where you feel like). Now simply insert the hall sensor facing forward (see datasheet). You might have to zig-zag the the pins on the end of the hall sensor - ensuring that it sits tight.
    5) Y-Magnet: First test the polarity of the magnet on the hall sensor endstop! Then place the magnet in its holder. During testing - If you messed up the Vcc, Gnd, Sig combination and made the Sig, Gnd, Vcc version you will see around 3 to 4 volt (Vcc=5V) if you placed it correct you will see Vcc. Moving the magnet to the sensor (with the right pole) will switch off the signal and give a like 50 mV.
    6) X-endstop: It can be mounted on my suggestion to the x-carriage (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:713073) in between the belts on either the motor or the idler part - very hard to take a picture of - sorry. The magnet fits into the x-carriage. You are done - enjoy.

description.text:
[ Patent Pending ]
Latest flight test video of Click! Adapters V0.9.23 by Zevi Rubin! VIDEO ==== 2015/06/11 ADDED NEW PROPELLER SIZES!! === As a new multi-rotor pilot who has gone through many broken props and lost screw caps, I wanted to create a better, more convenient prop adapter. It needed to:
  • Allow super quick prop changing.
  • Require no tools
  • Require no tightening, or human strength
  • Will not break mid air (the way a prop saver does)
  • Will not break before the prop breaks during crash
    • Designed to sit on top of a standard M5 Prop adapter. The base is locked down with a nut. (Lock tight can be used since this should not need to be removed often) This is now close to a final version. I really would like your thoughts so that I can continue to improve the design. I would like to invite my fellow pilots/printers to PTR (Print - Test - Report) === TESTS ===
    The follow is a list of things of things to test and report back. They should be performed in the provided order for safety. [Things to report on will be in square brackets]

  • Check the clip + unclip mechanism - DONE

  • Check that the clip holds on under varying loads - DONE

  • Test flight characteristics [Thrust][Flight Controller Sensors][Manoeuvrability][Vibrations] - DONE
    • === PART UPDATES ===
    2015/04/03 - Added thicker base to clear non-threaded section.
    2015/04/03 - Rotated parts for Ideal printing directionality.
    2015/04/05 - Several Changes to Tolerances and thicknesses. Adjusted cut - out for M5 Nut to fit more snugly
    2015/04/09 - Added shaft to clip to keep the fan centered
    2015/04/09 - Improved M5 Nut fit
    2015/04/09 - Several Improvements for Unclipping
    2015/04/09 - Lock-On Mechanism is more tolerant
    2015/05/06 - Clips now lock onto the propeller much more tight, removing and wiggle during flight.
    2015/05/06 - Added Designs for:
    Gemfan 5030 - 5045 - 6045
    HQ Prop 6045 === POST UPDATES ===
    2015/04/03 - Started a list of tests. 2015/04/03 - Ran some stress and displacement simulations. Here's the Report According the report (Obviously In Ideal Conditions and Non laminated ABS) - The component slips at between 200 - 300 N (approx 30kg of force) per prop adapter (Total of 120Kg for a Quad). The report provided is for 150N (Approx 15kg) per prop adapter. It gives me some piece of mind over the strength of the clips. This is only to meant provide some comfort in the design. Real life will not give these ideal results. 2015/05/20 - Zevi Rubin made a explanation video with the latest V0.9.23 Click! Adapters on 5030 - VIDEO === Credits === Thanks to the redditors that contributed to the discussion design.
    Special thanks to Zevi Rubin who did the first prints and ran the initial tests. See http://imgur.com/a/tF9ng For more information visit NimbleWings.com
